25. MODEL EVALUATION BASICS

After training, a model must be evaluated.

Why evaluation matters:
- To measure performance
- To compare models
- To detect weaknesses
- To decide whether deployment is appropriate

Common evaluation metrics depend on the task.

--------------------------------------------------
26. CLASSIFICATION METRICS

Accuracy
- Percentage of correct predictions overall

Precision
- Of the predicted positives, how many were actually positive?

Recall
- Of the actual positives, how many were correctly found?

Error Rate
- Percentage of incorrect predictions

Confusion Matrix
- Table showing correct and incorrect predictions by class

Important lesson:
Accuracy alone can be misleading, especially with imbalanced data.

--------------------------------------------------
27. CONFUSION MATRIX

A confusion matrix helps analyze classification results in more detail.

It shows:
- True Positives
- True Negatives
- False Positives
- False Negatives

Why it matters:
- Helps understand what kind of mistakes the model makes
- Useful when some errors are more costly than others

Example:
In fraud detection, missing fraud may be worse than falsely flagging a normal transaction.

--------------------------------------------------
28. REGRESSION METRICS

For regression, common metrics include:

Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
- Average absolute difference between predicted and actual values

Other regression metrics may exist, but MAE is a basic and useful one.

Lower error generally means better predictions.

--------------------------------------------------
29. WHY ACCURACY ALONE CAN MISLEAD

A model can have high accuracy but still be poor.

Example:
If 95% of emails are not spam, a model that always predicts “not spam” gets 95% accuracy but is useless for catching spam.

So evaluation should consider:
- Precision
- Recall
- Confusion matrix
- Business impact of errors

--------------------------------------------------
30. OVERFITTING AND UNDERFITTING

Overfitting:
- Model learns training data too closely
- Performs well on training data
- Performs poorly on new/unseen data

Underfitting:
- Model is too simple
- Fails to learn important patterns
- Performs poorly even on training data

Goal:
Find a model that generalizes well to new data.

--------------------------------------------------
31. TRAIN/TEST SPLIT

Data is often split into separate sets so evaluation is fair.

Typical idea:
- Training set: used to train the model
- Test set: used to evaluate performance on unseen data

This helps estimate how the model will perform in the real world.

--------------------------------------------------
32. MODEL TUNING

After initial evaluation, models can be improved by:
- Adjusting parameters
- Improving features
- Cleaning data better
- Trying different algorithms
- Collecting more relevant data

This is part of the iterative ML lifecycle.

--------------------------------------------------
